## Why He Runs to Death

Pheidippides carries shame he didn't choose — *nothos* status, a dead mother with secrets, a father he'll learn was the enemy of everything he believes in.

He runs to earn *kleos*, glory that might redeem a bloodline he can't escape. But *kleos* is selfish — it's glory for you, your name carved in stone. The arc is that he starts running for recognition and ends running for sacrifice. By the end, he no longer needs Athens to remember him. The act is enough.

The death run isn't suicide. It's transformation. He runs himself out of the human world and into legend.

